To everybody saying why Finns haven't pointed this out to him already: because to our ears, they don't really sound the same. The stress is on a different syllable, and there's a diphthong in the last vowel in 'viisaus', whereas in Vsauce, there's just a long vowel (and a different vowel from either of those making up the diphthong). If Vsauce was written according to Finnish orthography, it'd be something like 'vii soos' (two words since one way for Finns to separate one word from the previous one is to listen to where the main stress falls; it's always on the first syllable of the word, except in words that have no stress at all).

True about the dipthong, but Vsauce does actually have its stress on the first syllable, it's VEEsauce not viSAUCE. You seem to have gotten that mistaken idea that it's on the second one from a previous incorrect comment you replied to.

So the word "viisaus" has basically the same origin as the English word "wisdom", and same goes for "viisas" and "wise".

But also, it has the same origin as all the other words in Indo-European languages which come from the Indo-European root (which was related to both knowing and seeing) from which this Germanic root comes.

This includes "wit", of course, but also the Latin root related to seeing, so : in English, the words "visible", "vision", "video", and many other words, the Romance words for "to see" : Italian "vedere", Spanish and Portuguese "ver", French "voir" (past participle -> vu, from which the noun "vue", from which English "view"), Romanian "vedea", etc.

weirdly, Norwegian, Danish and Swedish both use visdom, but Icelandic doesn't, even though they are all Upper Germanic languages, so the concept, or at least word for, ~'the state of being wise' wasn't brought about until after Iceland was settled/established... potentially.

wis - dom

google only gives etymology of the word to middle english, nothing before

i feel like 'wis' probably comes from a common root of the German word 'wisse', meaning 'know'.

'dom'... ?... domain is the same word in English and German, and -dom as a suffix in English is reference to a domain, which originally just meant kingdom/land/etc., but I imagine the original word for domain became somewhat allusory* over time.

*allusory doesn't seemed to be recognized as a word outside of Wiktionary, but it seems to me to make fair enough sense, especially when considering the word illusory exists.

i could have gone with allusive, perhaps, but that makes me think of the word elusive.

...oddly, the etymology for elusive goes back to latin 'eludere', and the etymology for illusion goes back to latin 'illudere', which... i mean they must have come from the same word as some point... no?

aaaand, the etymology for allusion goes back to late latin 'alludere'... so there's that

'eludere' - latin, elusive
'illudere' - latin, to mock which eventually became to deceive, although I suspect along the lines of trick
'alludere' - late latin, from latin 'ad ludere' literally meaning 'to play towards'

while eludere and illudere may share a root, alludere certainly doesn't, as elusive and illusion could seemingly relate, allusion wouldn't.
